{"cursor":"31260","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fd/Rhof-flachsbearbeitung.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{taxobox |name = Flax |image =Linum_usitatissimum_-_KÃ¶hlerâs_Medizinal-Pflanzen-\n088.jpg |image_caption = Flax plant |regnum = Plantae |unranked_divisio =\nAngiosperms |unranked_classis = Eudicots |unranked_ordo = Rosids |ordo =\nMalpighiales |familia = Linaceae |genus = [[Linum]] |species = 'L.\nusitatissimum' |binomial = Linum usitatissimum |binomial_authority = Linnaeus.\n|}}\n'Flax' (also known as 'common flax' or 'linseed') (binomial name: 'Linum\nusitatissimum') is a member of the genus [[Linum]] in the family Linaceae. It is\nnative to the region extending from the eastern Mediterranean to India and was\nprobably first domesticated in the Fertile Crescent. Flax was extensively\ncultivated in ancient Ethiopia and ancient Egypt. [http://www.westonaprice.org/Flaxseed-and-Flaxseed-Oils-for-Omega-3-\nFatty-Acids.html ] A discovery reported in 2009 of spun, dyed, and knotted\nwild flax fibers in a prehistoric cave in the Republic of Georgia shows that the\nplant was already in use by humans at the surprisingly early date of 30,000\nB.C. Balter M. (2009). Clothes make the (Hu) Man. Science, 325(5946):1329.\nPMID 19745126 Kvavadze E, Bar-Yosef O, Belfer-Cohen A, Boaretto E,\nJakeli N, Matskevich Z, Meshveliani T. (2009).30,000-Year-Old Wild Flax Fibers.\nScience, 325(5946):1359. PMID 19745144\n[http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/data/325/5946/1359/DC1/1 Supporting Online\nMaterial] New Zealand flax is not related to flax but was named after it,\nas both plants are used to produce fibers.\n","linknr":655,"url":"Flax","recorded":1362373053,"links":104,"instances":["fruit","biology","flax","textiles","inventor"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Biodegradable materials","Fiber plants","Linum","Medicinal plants","Painting materials","Demulcents"],"headings":["Description","History","Uses","Cultivation","Production","Preparation for spinni